															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/monteparnas" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2926286); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2926286&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610163363" alt="Monteparnas" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2926286)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/monteparnas" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2926286); return false;" >Monteparnas</a></span> <span class="odate time_1558204241 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 May 2019 18:30</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4253594">
									

<p>I'm not sure about Tim Wilson <strong>not</strong> writing the critter profiles.</p>
<p>As far as I got it, WWS isn't that big a thing. Even with their pretty decent ability to get their hands on anomalies, they are still mostly the Non-profit, NGO they purport to be, and most of their actual work is still on normal animals. Then you get that most anomalies are tagged and released for surveillance, and those don't get Profiles, others are redeemed at least partially to the Foundation, and since they get proper SCP archives they don't get Profiles, either. The actual frequency of Critter Profiles being made is probably small.</p>
<p>Writing those Critter Profiles is a lot easier in-universe than out-of-universe, because it is just jotting down facts and things after all was said and done. The work that really is too much for Wilson to be doing personally all the time isn't done by him, it is to search, gather and tend to the several non-human guests and residents of the WWS. At this stage, writing the Profiles seems to me like the work that Wilson would actually want to do personally the most, because is above all his opportunity to be in touch with everything happening at WWS.</p>
<p>On the classification, this thing actually isn't too much more destructive than a normal locust swarm. Indeed it went undetected for quite some time, and was seemingly on the verge of annihilation when WWS found them. Even considering that normal locusts can lay as many as 150 eggs in the course of a month or so of reproductive time, this one doubling at an unspecified rate (but I think once a day is a reasonably safe assumption) isn't so much quicker than a common locust swarm to reproduce.</p>
<p>It is, indeed, a problem, and the WWS screwed up here, but I don't think that was so far-fetched. It was a reasonable mistake.</p>

							</div>

								
